    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-03-06T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-03-06T02:00:00-05:00" n="198"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d198">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./194: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_WJC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-03-06T10:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 6, 1935—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 6—8:09 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>88. My telegram No. 71, February 18, 4 p.m. <persName corresp="#p_DW1"
                        >Duranty</persName> confirms my impression that Soviet authorities are
                    becoming increasingly perturbed over relations with the United States and that
                    equanimity with which the termination of the Washington negotiations was first
                    greeted is being rapidly transformed into uneasiness. This is probably
                    attributable to growing realization of the fact that termination was not a mere
                    tactical maneuver. <persName corresp="#p_DW1">Duranty</persName> has just seen
                    his “number one Soviet contact” who is presumably high in party hierarchy.
                    Latter suggests possibility that as <persName corresp="#p_SIV1"
                        >Stalin</persName> attaches so much importance to Soviet-American relations
                    he might in the near future grant <persName corresp="#p_DW1">Duranty</persName>
                    an interview on the subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wiley</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
